My wife and I make this incredible dish at least once a week. Pancetta works well instead of bacon, and you can make a vinegarette with shallots for the dressing. Home-made croutons and a sprinkle of freshly grated parmesan are great additions as well.

Rating: 4
A couple tips. One classic version calls for poaching the eggs in red wine, which is wonderful. And I really don't recommend hardcooking the eggs; the runny yolk mixing with the greens and dressing is what makes the dish what it is.

Rating: 4
This turned out exactly like the Frisee Salad served at a restaurant (The Left Bank) near us. I've craved it ever since I had it there the first time and have been back for it numerous times. Now I can make it at home! I didn't have any red wine vinegar so I substituted champagne vinegar (about 2 Tbs + 1 tsp) and balsamic vinegar (about 2 tsp). They worked well together...the salad was heavenly.

Rating: 4
Reminds me of a salad I had at a bistro in Paris. Have made versions of it several times over the years. This was the best. If you're unsure of the freshness of your eggs, use hard-boiled instead of poached. Not quite authentic, nor as interesting, but still very good.

Rating: 4
Delicious-- we just served this as part of a brunch to some friends with very discerning palates, one of whom is a travel writer currently writing a book about France. It was a hit! Great for guests, because you can do practically everything in advance. Just poach the eggs the night before and slip them into an ice bath, then store covered in the fridge. Reheat in simmering water 1 min, then serve!

